18:18.973 --> 18:20.313
Because you know the police

18:20.391 --> 18:23.311
would be compelled
to go to Abernathy's barber shop...

18:24.562 --> 18:27.652
and go, "Have you ever heard of a fellow,
name of Norm Macdonald?"

18:27.732 --> 18:30.862
The guy goes, "Yeah, he would come in
every couple of months for a trim."

18:30.943 --> 18:34.863
"Oh, OK. Well, anyways,
he took his life because of you."

18:37.992 --> 18:40.622
"He wrote it here in this letter.
Would you like to keep the...?"

18:45.583 --> 18:49.053
Then Ralph Abernethy would have to spend
the rest of his life walking down...

18:55.593 --> 18:58.143
Life's hard enough
without having to walk...

19:07.813 --> 19:09.483
That's not a good practical joke.

19:09.565 --> 19:13.395
I should never have...
framed that as a good practical joke,

19:13.486 --> 19:16.066
because it's probably
the worst practical joke...

19:17.239 --> 19:18.239
You know?

19:19.241 --> 19:23.041
It's the kind of practical joke that gets
you raped by the devil for all of time.

19:32.046 --> 19:36.506
I uh came here from Las Vegas, Nevada,

19:36.592 --> 19:38.342
and when I was at the air...

19:38.427 --> 19:39.677
Uh...

19:39.762 --> 19:42.312
Where do airplanes go from? Airports.

19:44.225 --> 19:48.055
I was in the airport,
and guys were asking me for my ID,

19:48.145 --> 19:51.895
and it occurred to me
that ID is a strange abbreviation,

19:51.982 --> 19:54.692
because "I" is short for "I,"

19:54.777 --> 19:56.027
and then "D"...

19:57.071 --> 19:59.741
is short for "dentification," so...

20:01.992 --> 20:05.122
It seems to me
"D" is doing most of the...

20:06.789 --> 20:08.419
legwork on that one.

20:10.793 --> 20:12.093
But Vegas was cool.

20:13.671 --> 20:14.961
They have a motto in Vegas.

20:15.047 --> 20:16.917
They got their own slogan for the city.

20:17.007 --> 20:21.347
It says:
"What happens in Vegas stays in Vegas."

20:21.929 --> 20:22.929
Which is not true.

20:23.013 --> 20:26.273
You know, you can't kill a guy
and then just leave, you know?

20:27.226 --> 20:29.846
They'll follow you, they'll find you,

20:29.937 --> 20:33.687
they'll bring you back, and they'll
try you in front of a jury of your peers.

20:35.985 --> 20:38.895
So I thought, well,
what does it mean, anyways, you know?

20:38.988 --> 20:40.408
And I ruminated about it,

20:40.489 --> 20:43.119
days and days and nights.

20:44.702 --> 20:48.872
Sleepless weeks
became sleepless more weeks.

20:49.623 --> 20:52.503
And, finally, it occurred to me.

20:52.585 --> 20:53.875
It was so simple.

20:53.961 --> 20:56.131
It was right in front of my face
the entire time.

20:56.213 --> 20:58.053
"Whatever happens in Vegas
stays in Vegas,"

20:58.132 --> 21:00.682
all it really means
is you can go to Vegas,

21:00.760 --> 21:03.180
you can have sex with a prostitute...

21:05.556 --> 21:07.726
And she will not tell your wife.

21:10.936 --> 21:13.476
They're very discreet,

21:13.564 --> 21:16.364
the Las Vegas prostitutes.

21:17.401 --> 21:18.491
You know?

21:18.569 --> 21:20.279
Not like these gossipy,

21:20.362 --> 21:24.332
small-town whores
back where you live, you know?

21:24.408 --> 21:26.238
These fucking blabbermouths.

21:28.037 --> 21:31.417
Down at the beauty parlor
with that pale blue thing over their head,

21:31.499 --> 21:32.789
whatever the fuck that is.

21:34.126 --> 21:35.876
"Oh, you're Marge Majerson?"

21:35.961 --> 21:37.461
You're Neil's wife?

21:37.546 --> 21:39.216
"Well, by God!"

21:40.424 --> 21:42.554
"I took a shit on him last night..."

21:44.470 --> 21:46.060
"In exchange for cash."

21:48.474 --> 21:49.684
"Nice fella."

21:54.396 --> 21:57.936
My favorite thing
is the magic phones that we all have.

21:58.025 --> 21:59.435
You know,

21:59.527 --> 22:02.397
not so long ago, phones were not magic.

22:02.488 --> 22:04.488
They were just used to telephone people.

22:04.573 --> 22:07.953
And uh... they couldn't take pictures.

22:08.035 --> 22:09.075
You know?

22:09.161 --> 22:12.121
If you wanted to take a picture -
this was only, like, 20 years ago -

22:12.206 --> 22:14.706
you would have to use a...
you couldn't use a phone.

22:15.417 --> 22:16.627
I remember I tried.

22:16.710 --> 22:18.590
"OK, just hold on there. Just..."

22:19.922 --> 22:22.222
People go, "What are you doing?"
"Don't worry, it's..."

22:24.760 --> 22:26.890
I was kind of ahead of my time,
but they thought...

22:33.644 --> 22:35.854
No, you had to use a camera,

22:35.938 --> 22:38.228
and then you would put film in the camera,

22:38.315 --> 22:41.185
and then you would go to a Fotomat.

22:41.277 --> 22:42.277
It was wonderful.

22:42.361 --> 22:44.071
And you would give it to this old man,

22:44.154 --> 22:46.574
and he would go behind some beads
and stuff, you know?

22:49.034 --> 22:52.234
And then you go, "When am I going to see
them pictures?" He goes, "I don't know."

22:52.288 --> 22:53.288
And then you go...

22:53.998 --> 22:56.708
"I'll phone you every couple of weeks.
How would that be?"

22:59.169 --> 23:03.089
And then, one day,
you got the news your pictures were ready.

23:03.924 --> 23:07.644
And so you brought your whole family,
and you all showed up,

23:07.720 --> 23:09.260
and you got that envelope.

23:09.346 --> 23:10.596
It was wonderful.

23:10.681 --> 23:13.271
And you opened that seal, you know,

23:13.350 --> 23:16.400
and then there were the pictures -
a whole handful.

23:16.478 --> 23:18.078
Like, you would go, "Hey, look at this."

23:18.147 --> 23:21.187
It's a picture of Aunt Ida,

23:21.275 --> 23:23.775
"but her eyes are red like the devil."

23:27.364 --> 23:29.124
"Maybe Aunt Ida's the devil."

23:31.660 --> 23:32.660
"Hey, look at this!"

23:32.745 --> 23:34.325
It's a picture of my dog,

23:34.413 --> 23:38.043
"but I put a hat and glasses on it
so it would look like a person."

23:39.084 --> 23:41.214
"It still looks
kind of like a dog a little bit."

23:43.297 --> 23:45.467
"Hey, look, it's a picture of you!"

23:45.549 --> 23:47.219
But look at your jacket and your hair!

23:47.301 --> 23:48.511
"Ha!"

23:50.220 --> 23:52.430
"Look at the way you used to... Ha!"

23:52.931 --> 23:54.271
"Remember that hair?"

23:57.353 --> 24:02.273
So you needed that time for the picture
to make any sense or have any resonance.

24:04.234 --> 24:05.404
Nowadays, you go,

24:05.486 --> 24:07.356
"Hey, would you like to see a picture

24:07.446 --> 24:10.406
of you standing right where you are
one second ago?"

24:12.451 --> 24:13.581
"I got one here."

24:15.746 --> 24:17.326
"Your hair is identical."

24:18.916 --> 24:20.286
"I guess it would be, huh?"

24:26.090 --> 24:27.760
In the real old days,

24:27.841 --> 24:29.721
they would take pictures like...

24:29.802 --> 24:32.552
At my house I have a picture
of my great-grandfather,

24:32.638 --> 24:34.008
and I only have one, you know?

24:34.098 --> 24:37.428
Back then,
they only had one picture of everybody,

24:37.518 --> 24:40.978
because they would pull that thing,
and it would explode and all that shit.

24:42.773 --> 24:43.863
And it was just my...

24:43.941 --> 24:45.031
Nobody was happy...

24:46.068 --> 24:48.568
because it took so long
to get your picture taken.

24:48.654 --> 24:50.744
So it's just my great-grandfather like...

24:52.449 --> 24:54.279
"How long is this going to take, sir?"

24:57.246 --> 24:58.906
"Who's going to feed them hogs?"

25:02.000 --> 25:04.670
"It damn sure ain't going to be Marjorie,
I'll tell you that."

25:10.509 --> 25:13.889
Do you know what else I like
about the magic phone? Wikipedia.

25:14.555 --> 25:16.845
Oh, have you ever used that?
That's the best, man.

25:17.516 --> 25:21.396
It makes a democracy out of smartness.

25:22.062 --> 25:24.112
Everybody's equal now, you know?

25:24.189 --> 25:27.229
Used to be
a guy would go to school five, six years

25:27.317 --> 25:30.237
and then he would talk to me,
and I would be like, "Uh..."

25:30.320 --> 25:31.320
But now...

25:33.073 --> 25:34.533
Now it's all different...

25:35.659 --> 25:38.159
because I have got my magic phone
in my pocket.

25:38.704 --> 25:41.004
So a guy will say to me -
he'll go, "Hey, Norm",

25:41.081 --> 25:45.961
you ever hear of a fella
that went by the name of Claude Monet?"

25:48.213 --> 25:51.513
And I go, "Why, of course I have."

25:51.592 --> 25:52.972
I got to go to the bathroom."

25:55.304 --> 25:57.064
And then I go to the bathroom,

25:57.139 --> 25:59.679
and I'm in there 20-25 minutes,
and I come back.

26:00.851 --> 26:03.811
I go, "Hey, listen, I was just uh..."

26:03.896 --> 26:06.726
We were talking about Claude Monet,
and I just wanted to say

26:06.815 --> 26:11.355
"that, you know, what I liked about him
was his paintings."

26:14.573 --> 26:16.953
"I like the way he painted."

26:17.034 --> 26:18.744
He was a painter,

26:18.827 --> 26:23.207
"and I loved how he used the paint
to make paintings."

26:27.377 --> 26:29.297
And then the guy goes, "Goddamn, Norm!"

26:29.922 --> 26:32.382
"I've never been able
to stump you in two years."

26:42.267 --> 26:45.267
But I looked on my...
Because I like learning on my Wikipedia.

26:45.354 --> 26:48.574
And I looked, because I was wondering
about fame, the nature of fame,

26:48.649 --> 26:50.979
because it's changed so much, you know?

26:51.068 --> 26:53.028
And when I was young it was one thing,

26:53.111 --> 26:54.911
and now it's a whole different thing.

26:55.447 --> 26:59.737
And uh I was wondering
how many people have been to the moon -

26:59.827 --> 27:02.157
like, have actually walked on the moon.

27:02.246 --> 27:05.536
So I looked on my magic telephone
and I found out.

27:06.166 --> 27:11.206
Only 14 - 13 or 14 -
in the entire history of the world.

27:11.296 --> 27:15.256
You would think
that would make you very, very famous.

27:15.759 --> 27:16.759
But no.

27:18.929 --> 27:20.599
The last guy who walked...

27:20.681 --> 27:24.141
Now, you think he would be famous
for being the last guy to be on the moon.

27:24.226 --> 27:26.056
His name was Harrison Schmitt.

27:27.688 --> 27:29.228
Now, whoever heard of him?

27:30.941 --> 27:32.991
Meanwhile,
he goes all the way to the moon,

27:33.068 --> 27:35.278
hangs around there for a while
and comes back.

27:35.988 --> 27:37.448
He's not famous,

27:37.531 --> 27:40.331
but a girl with a giant ass is famous.

27:43.537 --> 27:45.497
Now, when I was young,

27:45.581 --> 27:48.131
a man who went to the moon was famous,

27:48.208 --> 27:50.128
and a lady with a giant ass, you would go,

27:50.210 --> 27:52.460
"Can you stand over there?
Because this is..."

28:00.470 --> 28:02.140
Harrison Schmitt.

28:04.641 --> 28:07.311
So how many people that went to the moon
do we even know?

28:07.394 --> 28:09.154
There was... We know the first ones.

28:09.229 --> 28:11.269
There was Neil Armstrong, Buzz Aldrin.

28:11.356 --> 28:14.106
They went in Apollo 11 -
Neil Armstrong, Buzz Aldrin.

28:14.192 --> 28:17.912
And even the third is hard to remember.
His name is Michael Collins.

28:17.988 --> 28:19.908
And Michael Collins,

28:19.990 --> 28:21.160
in one of the...

28:22.284 --> 28:25.334
just most unfair jokes -

28:25.412 --> 28:27.122
I don't know what it was -

28:27.205 --> 28:31.165
he got to go all the way to the moon
but not go on the moon.

28:36.506 --> 28:38.256
All the way to the moon,

28:38.342 --> 28:40.682
and then, that little rope ladder,

28:40.761 --> 28:42.261
he wasn't allowed to go down.

28:44.848 --> 28:47.518
He had to stay in the lunar capsule...

28:49.228 --> 28:52.728
while Buzz Aldrin and Neil Armstrong
went on the moon.

28:52.814 --> 28:55.234
Michael Collins
just looking out the window, going...

28:57.027 --> 28:59.147
"Are those motherfuckers golfing?!"

29:03.909 --> 29:05.659
"Good God! They're golfing!"

29:07.329 --> 29:09.999
"Wait a minute, they...
they have got a dune buggy now!"

29:12.793 --> 29:16.883
"I was only allowed to bring so much
and they brought dune buggies.

29:16.964 --> 29:17.974
This is..."

29:18.507 --> 29:21.127
"I have to keep up
a good face, I guess."

29:26.181 --> 29:28.641
And then Buzz and Neil,
I'm sure they were nice guys,

29:28.725 --> 29:31.135
they didn't want to hurt Michael Collins,
you know?

29:31.228 --> 29:35.228
So they probably went back, you know,
to the lunar capsule, you know,

29:35.315 --> 29:38.935
and Michael Collins was like, "What do you
think, guys? What was the moon like?"

29:39.027 --> 29:40.527
And they were like, "Ah."

29:43.323 --> 29:46.543
"It was all right
if you like that kind of thing, I guess."

29:50.414 --> 29:53.674
"I prefer the lunar capsule myself. I..."

29:54.835 --> 29:56.795
"I can't speak for Buzz, but..."

29:58.380 --> 30:00.340
"I really do like the lunar capsule."

30:06.972 --> 30:10.352
Because that's what you do.
You know, most of your life is mundane.

30:10.434 --> 30:13.904
I decided to write a book, right?
So, it was a book about my life.

30:13.979 --> 30:16.149
They said, "Just write about your life,"
so I said...

30:17.349 --> 30:19.859
Oh, thank you. Yeah. Yeah.

30:19.943 --> 30:22.403
It turned out to be
the greatest comic novel ever written,

30:22.487 --> 30:27.987
but when it started
it was supposed to be a memoir, you know?

30:28.076 --> 30:30.696
A... An autobiography.

30:30.787 --> 30:33.787
So it makes you think,
"Well, what is my life?"

30:33.874 --> 30:35.424
So I started thinking about it, right?

30:35.500 --> 30:37.750
So I said, "OK, I wake up in the morning",

30:37.836 --> 30:40.166
and I eat some Count Chocula."

30:42.632 --> 30:47.102
And then I watch <i>Sports Center</i>
while I'm digesting my Count Chocula,

30:47.179 --> 30:50.179
and I phone my friend Fat Freddie.

30:50.766 --> 30:52.386
And I go, "Hey."

30:52.476 --> 30:55.936
You want to eat a cheese sandwich
or something around three o'clock?

30:56.021 --> 30:59.901
I... I got to wait
for my Count Chocula to digest,

30:59.983 --> 31:02.243
"but how does that settle with you?"

31:02.319 --> 31:05.609
He goes, "Yeah, great,"
so I get together with him.

31:05.697 --> 31:09.527
And on my way, I get some groceries
to bring home for later,

31:09.618 --> 31:12.908
and uh... and then, of course,
there's dinner, you know?

31:13.538 --> 31:16.498
So most of my life

31:16.583 --> 31:20.593
is finding and consuming food.

31:23.298 --> 31:26.008
So it doesn't make for a riveting read.

31:30.847 --> 31:33.137
It's incredibly repetitious.

31:39.856 --> 31:41.686
When you're writing, you learn a lot.

31:41.775 --> 31:43.855
I went to a guy who's a big writer guy.

31:43.944 --> 31:46.074
He told me about things
I didn't know about.

31:46.154 --> 31:48.164
Metaphors - have you ever heard of them?

31:49.741 --> 31:52.451
He said, "You have got to use metaphors."
I'm like, "What's that?"

31:52.953 --> 31:54.333
He was like, "That's a thing."

31:54.413 --> 31:55.753
So, a metaphor is like,

31:55.831 --> 31:57.961
'You can lead a horse to water,

31:58.041 --> 32:00.131
"but you can't make it drink.'"

32:00.210 --> 32:01.920
I'm like, "What the fuck does that mean?"

32:02.003 --> 32:03.213
So he was like,

32:03.296 --> 32:06.336
"That means you can take a person,
you know,"

32:06.425 --> 32:09.295
and you can give them
all the information and everything,

32:09.386 --> 32:13.636
"but he still has to be the one
to absorb it himself."

32:13.723 --> 32:16.693
So I was like, "Well, why the fuck
didn't you just say that? Like, what..."

32:19.062 --> 32:21.362
"Why did you have to put a horse into it?
Like, what..."

32:23.275 --> 32:27.195
"You thought I was so stupid you needed
to make it into some fable? Like, what..."

32:28.113 --> 32:29.363
"A horse?"

32:33.285 --> 32:36.955
"Or sometimes
the metaphor part of it is true,"

32:37.038 --> 32:39.368
but then the literal part is not true.

32:39.458 --> 32:45.008
They will go, like, 'That which does not
kill you makes you stronger, ' right?

32:45.088 --> 32:47.088
Now, metaphorically, that's true,

32:47.174 --> 32:49.934
like maybe a woman
breaks your heart, you know,

32:50.010 --> 32:52.180
or life deals you a bad hand.

32:52.262 --> 32:55.352
And then the next time
you're prepared for it

32:55.432 --> 32:57.932
"and uh...
and it doesn't hurt you as much."

32:58.643 --> 33:00.813
"But, literally, it's not true at all."

33:00.896 --> 33:05.186
Literally it's, 'That which does not
kill you makes you weaker...

33:07.486 --> 33:10.816
"And will probably kill you
the next time it shows up.'"

33:16.786 --> 33:19.536
That's why I like - personally -

33:19.623 --> 33:24.883
I like the ones where the metaphor is true
and the literal part is true.

33:24.961 --> 33:27.841
Like... They say, like,
"Beauty is only skin deep."

33:27.923 --> 33:30.013
I think that's beautiful, because it is.

33:30.091 --> 33:31.891
Like, you know, really,

33:31.968 --> 33:34.548
what makes a person attractive
is what's inside -

33:34.638 --> 33:38.018
their friendship,
their conviviality, their goodwill,

33:38.099 --> 33:42.309
not this uh... optic trick, you know?

33:43.396 --> 33:46.396
And so it has that,
but also, literally it's true,

33:46.483 --> 33:50.533
because you could be
the handsomest guy in the world, you know?

33:50.612 --> 33:53.742
You could have, like, this chiseled jaw

33:53.823 --> 33:57.243
and beautiful,
thick mane of hair, you know?

33:57.786 --> 34:00.866
Large shoulders and narrow waist.

34:00.956 --> 34:02.116
Are you guys horny?

34:03.500 --> 34:04.670
Is it just me, or...?

34:08.964 --> 34:11.424
Giant quads, a perfect body.

34:11.507 --> 34:14.138
Six percent body fat, you know?

34:17.429 --> 34:20.139
But you take that same guy

34:20.225 --> 34:21.344
and you skin him.

34:29.192 --> 34:30.572
All of a sudden...

34:34.155 --> 34:36.945
he is not so easy on the eye.

34:47.918 --> 34:49.248
I'm getting old, you know?

34:50.297 --> 34:53.427
I asked my doctor...
This is interesting, because I wondered...

34:53.507 --> 34:56.598
You know,
I know the first two causes of death -

34:56.678 --> 34:59.098
heart disease and cancer,

34:59.180 --> 35:01.060
neck and neck, you know, to kill you.

35:01.141 --> 35:05.441
So I said to the doctor, "What's
the third most common cause of death?"

35:05.520 --> 35:06.650
What is the third?"

35:06.730 --> 35:09.860
And he said, "Complications."

35:11.443 --> 35:13.953
That's...
That's like the doctor fucking up.

35:14.029 --> 35:15.199
Like, how is that the third?

35:15.864 --> 35:17.074
That's the third?

35:20.827 --> 35:25.957
You go, "Hey, Doc, I can't help
but noticing my father is dead uh..."

35:27.417 --> 35:31.167
"And I remember yesterday
you said it was a simple operation."

35:32.130 --> 35:34.670
And he was like,
"Yeah, we thought it was."

35:35.675 --> 35:37.715
"Looked simple in the book,
I'll tell you that."

35:38.553 --> 35:42.773
"But uh...
you cut open a man, by God, it's..."

35:44.309 --> 35:46.809
"All this red stringy stuff
and everything."

35:48.438 --> 35:49.648
"Are you a doctor?" "No."

35:49.731 --> 35:51.441
"Ah, you wouldn't have heard.

35:51.524 --> 35:53.324
Way too complicated for you."

35:56.196 --> 35:58.196
But you worry when you get old, you know?

35:58.281 --> 36:00.951
You get concerned, scared.

36:02.535 --> 36:04.365
I remember my grandmother, you know,

36:04.454 --> 36:07.874
she was like... I think she was like 85
at the time or something,

36:07.957 --> 36:11.667
and I looked at her - she was sitting in
her chair - and I said, "Hey, Grandma."

36:11.753 --> 36:13.003
She had a bruise, right?

36:13.088 --> 36:15.168
And it went from her... from her wrist,

36:15.256 --> 36:18.426
all the way up her arm,
right to her shoulder.

36:18.510 --> 36:20.100
A big bruise -

36:20.178 --> 36:23.258
purple, green and yellow.

36:24.766 --> 36:26.056
A third of each.

36:26.142 --> 36:27.482
And I said...

36:27.560 --> 36:31.190
I said,
"Grandma, where did you get that bruise?"

36:31.272 --> 36:34.072
and then my grandmother said, "The wind."

36:37.821 --> 36:39.071
I said, "The wind?"

36:40.949 --> 36:44.199
And she said, "Yes. Do you remember
that gentle breeze yesterday?"

